#
OFFER RENT

For use in the receptions of inns.

Offer makes the innkeeper tell you the cost of storing your belongings
for one day.  Rent stores you belongings and exits you from the game.
When you re-enter, you will start where you rented.

There is a daily charge for rent.  You may store your things at the
CRYOGENIC CENTER for a one-time charge of four days rent.  See INNS
for details on the rent policy.

> offer
> rent

See also: INNS
#
OGRE

As a general rule, Ogres are big, mean, and dumb.  They make wonderful
warriors but generally feeble wizards and clerics, due to their innate
tendencies towards high strength and constitution and low intelligence
and wisdom. Their great size is often of use in combat as well, making
them excellent bashers. They are fond of treasure, and are often employed 
as mercenaries by evil races in particular. They tend to have yellowish 
hides, are covered with wart-like bumps, have black teeth and talons, and 
purplish eyes with white pupils. Ogres are exceptionally strong and hardy, 
but are known to be extremely dim-witted and lacking in wisdom. They are 
excellent in melee combat, but are extremely limited when they attempt to 
utilize magic. Ogre mages and clerics, rare though they may be,
are not unknown to the realms.

Ogres do not like little creatures, who tend to cause problems and/or
steal things.  If they cannot be bullied, they should be smashed.
#
OPEN CLOSE LOCK UNLOCK

To open, close, lock, and unlock doors, of course.

<open | close | lock | unlock> <door [direction]>|<obj>|<direction>

> open portal
> lock door
> unlock door south
> close gate    
> open chest
> open north
#
ORC

A bit slow and a bit dumb, Orcs are nevertheless know to be tough, wily
and strong foes worthy of one's respect.  Slightly larger than a human,
Orcs prefer the dark confines of underground caverns and the hidden
realms of the underworld to the light of day, and will emerge into
sunlight on only the dimest of days, if they can help it, and only after
expressing their dismay at having to suffer from 'that accursed
brightness.'
#
ORDER

Used for ordering pets and charmed people to do your evil bidding.  You
can order everyone under your command with "order followers".

order <character> <command>
order followers <command>

> order puppy eat bread
> order cityguard sleep

See also:  CHARM
#
PKILL

When a player (CH) kills another player (Victim) it is called a PKILL.
CH will gain a pkscore points, cks (clan score) points if in clan and
a message will be published on INFO channel. Of course, all of the 
victim's equipment may now change it's owner as well. Important thing
is that the victim does not lose any experience, but only suffers the
humiliation and the equipment lost. You may not try to attack a player who 
is more then ten levels below your level.

See Also: CLAN
#
POISON

Effects of poison may vary as there are many poisons known and still
unknown. Usually poison deals some amount of damage each tick and
reduces your regeneration significantly, while lowering your strength and
constitution. You body will fight the poison, and depending upon your
constitution, eventually cure it. Poison can also be removed by some
healing spells. You should try to find a local healer should you need
poison removed.
#
POUR

If you want to pour some liquid from one container to another.

> pour canteen cup

See also: FILL
#
PRACTICE PRACTISE

Practice is the way you improve your spells and skills. You must go to
your guildmaster to let him/her help you improve.
If you type practice, you will see which skills you can improve upon, and
how good you already are at these.
You can then use practice <skill>, to practice the appropriate skill.
You can only practise a certain amount for each level you gain, and you
do not have to save this, it can be accumulated.
#
PROMPT "COMBAT PROMPT"

Usage: prompt <"combat"> <prompt string>

This command sets your prompt. You may also set your combat prompt which is
automatically switched to when you engage in combat. You may use any
combination of characters in your prompt. Available special codes are:


%n :  your character name                           
%h :  current hit points                            
%H :  maximum hit points                            
%m :  current mana points                       
%M :  maximum mana points                       
%v :  current movement points                       
%V :  maximum movement points                               
%l :  current mana leech       
%x :  exp until next level
%X :  current exp
%g :  gold carried


                                  
%e :  visible exits
%w :  your wait lag in seconds (useful in combat)

%d :  opponent's condition (descriptive)              
%o :  opponent's condition (percentage)               
%0:   opponent's name                                 

%t :  tanker's condition	                                              
%j :  group member with lowest hit points	      
%k :  group member with lowest hit points (percentage)			
%b :  group member with lowest movement points	      

%^ :  a new line  
%% :  percent sign

There is one special code:
%a'name' : If you are affected by skill/spell of given name, first letter of
           that spell/skill will be returned. For example:
           > prompt (%a'hide'%a'sanc'%a'fly') %h/%H>
           If you want to use more then one skill/spell with the same first
           letter, it is advisable to use color codes.

&c'prompt default' will set prompt to "%hH %mM %vV %e>"
'prompt combat default' will set combat prompt to "%hH %mM %vV [%O: %d]> "&0

You can also use ANSI colors in your prompt. See help on ANSI for color codes.

See also:  TOGGLE, ANSI
#
PUSH DRAG

Usage: push <character | object> <direction>
       drag <character | object> <direction>
       
       
You may use push command to push someone or something out of the room.
Example:
> push guard north

Drag command is similar to push except that you will also move in desired
direction, together with your target. Also, target must be at least in
sitting position in order to be draged (that means it must be on the ground).

> drag corpse south
> drag fido west

Success depends upon your strength versus target's strength and their weight.
PUSH and DRAG skills further improve your chances.
#
PUT

For putting items into containers.

> put bread bag
> put all.bread bag
> put all chest

See also: GET
#
QSAY

To tell something to everyone on the quest channel.

See also: QUEST
#
QUAFF POTION POTIONS

Usage: quaff <potion>

Quaff is used to "drink" a (magical) potion.  The magic will take effect 
immediately, for better or for worse...

       
Potions are typically used to augment spells and for healing in the aftermath
of battles, but quaffing in combat is possible.
  
You may quaff in battle, but must perform a check against your dexterity
with the following cumulative modifiers:
  
        -4      if fighting, as your attention is somewhat distracted by your
                eager opponent trying to remove all your limbs from your body

        -4      if wielding a weapon, as you must now defer to your offhand

        -4      if wielding a weapon and a shield, as now you require a third
                hand which you have just discovered that you do not have

        +5      if you have the potion already held (hold potion)

If you fail your check, the potion will break.

As potions take some time to get, uncap and quaff, a slight delay will 
result before you actually quaff the potion.

See also: RECITE
#
QUEST

QUEST commands: POINTS INFO TIME REQUEST COMPLETE LIST BUY.

POINTS will show how many quest points do you have. You can also view this 
with SCORE or WORTHY commands. You use your quest points to QUEST BUY some 
items. You can view a list of items available for purchase with the QUEST 
LIST command. Both of these commands are only available when you are at 
your questmaster's location (for example Willie in the Midgaard Zoo). These 
items can not be found or bought anywhere else. QUEST TIME will show the 
remaining time for the completition of your quest. QUEST INFO will inform 
you briefly about your quest. QUEST REQUEST will assign you a quest if one 
is available. You can do only one quest at a time. When you finish your 
quest, go to your questmaster and type QUEST COMPLETE.

If there was a reboot during your quest, just type 'quest info' afterwards,
which will make sure you don't lose any quest points.


See also:  QSAY
#
QUI SHUTDOW

Just to prevent accidental quittings and/or shutdowns.
This command doesn't DO anything, it simply is.
#
QUICKTHROW

Usage: quickthrow <object>

Quickthrow can be used to throw objects at your enemy while fighting,
causing damage. Thrown objects will deal damage proportional to their
damage dice, or if not weapons, to their weight. To get the full effect
of throwing things at mobs, it is best to practice the thief skill
'knife throwing'.

See also: THROW SHOOT 
#
QUIT

When you get tired of playing, you can leave the game by typing 'quit'.
Note that quitting this way causes any items you might be carrying to
simply be left on the ground.  If you wish to have your equipment stored,
you'll have to find an inn and pay rent.

See also: INN
#
RACE

Try help on a specific rade ie. 'help troll'
#
RANGER

  The history of the ranger is as long as it is interesting. Rangers
were first used in the great wars as quick moving, lightly armored
scouts during the ancient wars. Later, they were known as heavy
hitting elite strike forces with extensive training in woodcraft and
wilderness survival. In the peaceful years before the current era
they were primarily caretakers of the forests and wilder wilderness
areas near the big cities. In the current era of constant conflict
and wars, the Rangers are great survivors.

The following spells are available to ranger:
Level    Spell                         Level    Spell
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
4 : Cure poison                        20: Arrow rain
6 : Infravision                        21: Protection from fire
8 : Create spring                      22: Surcease
9 : Protection from lightning          24: Blindness
10: Barkskin                           26: Eagle eye
11: Cure blindness                     28: Refresh
13: Protection from coldness           29: Web
15: Endurance                          31: Stoneskin
17: Faerie fire                        33: Call lightning
19: Sense life


The following skills are available to ranger:
Level    Skill                         Level    Skill
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
1 : Fillet, Cook, Enhanced sight       16: Elbow swing
2 : First aid                          17: Hunt
3 : Archery                            18: Shield block, Bash
4 : Track                              19: Dual wield
5 : Kick                               riposte?
6 : Consider                           21: Retreat
7 : Parry                              22: Knee thrust
8 : Forage                             23: Disarm
9 : Trip                               24: Spring leap
10: Sneak                              25: Third attack
11: Rescue                             27: Medic
12: Second attack                      30: Sweepkick
13: Cover tracks, Sharpen              32: Guard ???
14: Map terrain                        35: Whirlwind
15: Autopsy                            39: Combo

Ranger's teacher is trusty John the Lumberjack, and he can be often found
in Haon-Dor forest, near his wooden cabin.
#
READ

When you want to read something.

READ is also used to read messages on bulletin boards; type HELP BOARDS
for more information.

> read note

See also: BOARDS
#
RECITE SCROLL SCROLLS

Use : Recite <Scroll> [Target]

Is used to "read" a magical scroll. Target can be an object, character or
nothing (which may be yourself).
 
You may recite scrolls in battle, but must perform a check against your 
dexterity with the following cumulative modifiers:
  
    -4      if fighting, as your attention is somewhat distracted by your
            eager opponent trying to remove all your limbs from your body

    -4      if wielding a weapon, as you must now defer to your offhand

    -4      if wielding a weapon and a shield, as now you require a third
            hand which you have just discovered that you do not have

    +5      if you already have the scroll prepared in your hand (hold scroll)

If you fail your check, the scroll will probably tear apart. While reciting
a scroll you will not be able to attack and your defense will be somewhat
weaker.

See also: QUAFF
#
REGENERATION

This shows you how fast you regenerate your hitpoints, mana and move per
tick.
Maximum regeneration that you can have is 1/4 of your points. So, if you
have 600 mana points, you have maximum regen of 150 mana per tick. 

See also: REGENERATE
#
REMOVE

If you tire of wearing some armor or wielding a weapon.

> remove boots
> remove sword
> remove all
> remove all.bronze

See also: WEAR, WIELD
#
REPEAT

Use REPEAT to control whether or not the mud echoes your communication 
commands to you (i.e. the MUD will tell you what you just said, group-said,
shouted, or told someone).  This is useful to verify what you just said, 
but can be annoying if you have a slow link.

See also:  SAY GSAY TELL SHOUT HOLLER
#
REPLAY

REPLAY displays the last 10 tells you received. This is quite useful for
the tells you tend to miss during battles.
#
REPORT

This command sends a report of your current and max hp and mana to your
group.  You can use this command to let potential rescuers know how
low your hps are without forcing them to use the "group" command.  It is
designed as a convenience for groups with members who get lag or have slow
modems.

> report
#
RESIZE

Syntax: resize <number_of_lines>

This command will set your current screen settings used when DISPLAY is set 
to VT100. By default it is set to 24.

See also: DISPLAY TOGGLE
#
RSTAT

RSTAT shows room stats, just like 'STAT ROOM', but allows you to stat 
remote rooms.  If no room is specified, you will see the stats of the 
room you are currently in.

rstat [room #]

> rstat
> rstat 3001

See also:  RSET
#
SACRIFICE

usage: sacrifice <obj>

With this command you offer a sacrifice to your God. Depending on the value of
the sacrifice you may be awarded or even punished.

See also: AUTOSAC
